data.value:
Gemini is a constellation in the northern sky. This constellation has been described by cultures since ancient times, and is still one of the most well known throughout the world. The best time to view Gemini is during February; by April and May, the constellation can be seen soon after sunset in the west.
Gemini is Latin for “twins”. Many different cultures have associated this constellation with twins, but one of the better known myths is that of Castor and Pollux. These two boys had an interesting story; Pollux was the son of Zeus and a mortal woman named Leda, while Castor was the son of the King, Tyndareus of Sparta and Leda. Despite the different parentage, the two were still twins. Throughout their lives, Castor and Pollux proved their cunning and worth through their fighting ability. Eventually, Castor died. Castor was only mortal, while Pollux was immortal due to his father Zeus. Pollux begged his father to give Castor immortality, so they’d never be apart. In response, Zeus united them in the heavens.
Gemini is also the radiant point for a meteor shower known as the Geminids, which happen every year around mid-December. Astronomers say that the Geminid display is one of the best annual meteor showers because the individual meteors are bright and move quickly.
